153. Jam senis,] ‘Jam' is only em- phatic, like ἥδη. The coachman is not ashamed to meet his friend, though quite an old man, whom he ought to have blushed to meet. He recognizes him first and sa- lutes him with his whip, as we see drivers do now, turning up the butt end as they pass an acquaintance. Dion Cassius (77. 10) says of the Emperor Caracalla, who was given, among his idle and profligate habits, to driving, προσεκύνει αὐτοὺς κάτωθεν τῇ μάστιγι, meaning by αὐτούς the specta- tors.
